This has been great experience and allowed us to start doing some serious predictive modelling. Although the package allows us to estimate models that we might not be able to use otherwise, it requires significant RAM to iterate over numerous cohorts of customers in our database. I started running this R code using the {BTYD} package on my local machine, then moved it to a remote desktop to get more RAM, but still had to upgrade the RAM on this machine to 16Gb in order for the code to run without getting memory errors. This has made it clear to our leadership team that we need to find a longer-term solution to running more advanced  statistical and machine learning methods in R.  
  
 In terms of the analytics team at Clearly - I am the Senior Analyst, focused on web analytics. I have an intern who started about 4 months ago, but will be joining the team full-time after her internship is over. We also have a Senior Analyst on our BI team who primarily uses SPSS for building models, and a Data Analyst Lead on the BI team who mostly uses SQL and Excel. They are all starting out in R, but I'm hoping that they will become power users of R as well. 
  
 I'd like to discuss RStudio Server Pro and what it can offer. In particular: 
 -Pricing 
 -Scaling compute and RAM to meet the demands of the team 
 -Enterprise-level support for R 
 -Improving productivity in R 
 -Collaborating on projects in R 
 -Using git in RStudio 
 -Security of our data 
 -Publishing R Markdown reports and Shiny Apps that execs and business users can access 
  
 Thanks!

Title: booked: Paris Tolmachoff parist@mcm.com
NAME: Paris Tolmachoff
NOTES:
Interested in hearing about the capabilities of Rstudio connect.  w have several heavy R users and develop shiny apps, documents and presentations. 
  
 Would like to shorten the learning curve and make more robust the process of deploying apps/documents, with baked in version/package dependency management. 
  
 Also, the main users/developers of R are business users (data scientists, analysts, etc), and we would like to transfer as much of the dev ops, sys admin responsibilities to the IT department in order for them to focus more on just the analytics portion.   It would be good to get an understanding of how system administrators, with no R knowledge, could help manage the system. 
  
 We have played around a little but with the beta server that is open to the public, but it would be great to get a live demo so we can get a better understanding of all the capabilities. 
  
 Also, based on our research we have several specific questions: 
  
 •	How easily can the downtime of the server be managed by people with no R experience (i.e. system admins) 
 •	Is there ability to roll back versions of applications or documents? 
 •	Ability to organize apps/documents in folders? 
 •	Ability to schedule reports via trigger (i.e. touch a file)? 
 a.	Or via api call 
 •	More custom scheduling options? 
 a.	Weekends? 
 b.	Multiple schedules, i.e. run every minute, email every day 
 c.	Can the scheduler save copies with datestamp? 
 •	Performance of applications compared to open source Shiny Server? 
 •	Ability to load balance across multiple nodes? 
  
  
 Look forward to chatting with you.  
  
 Specific question

Title: booked: Peter Crosbie pjcrosbie@turingriskadvisors.com
NAME: Peter Crosbie
NOTES:
workflow and data file management 
  
 I use git to manage versions of .Rmd, .R and other src files. My data files are generally too large to store in git, say .5 - 3 GB. My projects involve "data analysis" / "modeling" that progresses in a daisy chain as I clean up the data and then into a multi branch tree as I try different approaches. The datafiles and src files are linked logically (in the sense   the src files "transform" the datafiles).  
  
 I have to believe that this is a common enough set of circumstances and thus I'm honestly surprised that there aren't more tools/packages available to somehow "stamping" and "versioning" data files. For example, if I look at a datafile, can I tell what script created it and when?  
  
 I do some of this now but it is ad hox and hacky because I wrote it. Essentially I use rstudioapi to get name of file and attach that either as an attribute or in a text file as a data dictionary. 
  
 It will do but isn't there a better way - there are just so many clever people using R I keep thinking I must be reinventing the wheel.

Title: booked: Vergil Weatherford vergil.weatherford@navigant.com
NAME: Vergil Weatherford
NOTES:
Hey Aaron, 
  
 Thanks for checking in.  We actually had three from our team at rstudio::conf() this year—Thomas, Jeff, and Dan. They had a great time and brought back a lot of new knowledge, just as Ryan, Chris, and I did last year. Props for putting together a great conference! 
  
 I would be glad to have another check-in call next week.  Our group tracks RStudio product news and updates pretty closely, so for the most part we don’t need feature demos or updates (we’re giving those internally). We’re making use of RStudio’s new database features and we’re working on building out a companion Spark cluster that our team can plug into via sparklyr. 
  
 What we could use help with is brainstorming how to help Shiny/RSConnect catch on internally. Approval for licensing Pro Shiny/RSConnect servers has run into some resistance at the corporate level given that corporate has a preference for Spotfire as I mentioned before (we have a lot more point-and-click technical staff in the company than than R programming staff). We still have users taking advantage of RStudio’s dashboarding/reporting tools internally to our team, just using open-source shiny server. I’m hoping to make the case to corporate that Shiny is the right tool for certain client projects especially for our R users, but it’s an uphill battle—they want to standardize around a single tool for all of Navigant, which I certainly understand. Any help you can provide us would be great.  We have R users excited to use Shiny and RSConnect, but don’t yet have the political clout to get funding for Pro licenses. 
  
 In other news, we do have other practices at Navigant starting to adopt R, so our RSP infrastructure team is looking into potentially replicating what we’ve done in the Energy practice in other places. Potential for the need for more RSP licensing in the future. We might be interested in hearing about your new “hot-swappable” licensing and what use cases that’s intended for (thus far, we haven’t “containerized” our RSP cluster, and adding servers is a once-a-year operation as demand grows slowly over time). 
  
 I’ll set up a time with a couple folks from our team and look forward to speaking with you next week. 
  
 Best, 
 Vergil
